The Quad Leaders' Summit, attended by the Prime Ministers of Australia, India, Japan, and the President of the United States, was held in Hiroshima. The leaders reaffirmed their commitment to a free and open Indo-Pacific region and emphasized the importance of working together to navigate the changing global strategic and economic environment. They expressed their belief that all countries have a role in contributing to regional peace, stability, and prosperity, and in upholding international law and the rules-based international order. The leaders discussed various areas of cooperation, including climate change, health security, infrastructure development, digital connectivity, and maritime domain awareness. They also expressed their concerns over issues such as the militarization of disputed features in the East and South China Seas, the war in Ukraine, North Korea's missile launches, and the situation in Myanmar. The leaders announced several initiatives and partnerships to enhance cooperation in these areas and reaffirmed their commitment to the Quad's positive and practical agenda. The next Quad Leaders' Summit will be hosted by India in 2024.